The International Financial Corporation (IFC)  sold its 10 percent stake in the Nomura Hungarian Investment Bank to the main  shareholder, Japanese Nomura Securities Co, the bank's deputy managing  director said Friday.
After the sale, Nomura Securities holds a 76-percent stake in the bank  with the AB-Aegon insurance company holding the rest, director Laszlo Kovacs  Florian said.
The bank, which plans to extend capital investment services for its  clients this year, had a pre-tax profit of 26 million forints (more than  252,000 dollars) and an after-tax profit of 15 million forints (almost 146,000  dollars) last year on a balance sheet total of 1.037 billion forints (more  than 10 million dollars), he said.
